wen i was young i worked selling candies and one day i got enough money to spend on something nice before going home.
So i stopped at a popular dumpling shop and i ordered 9 shumai for me and my girlfriend to share. I spent the time waiting by playing arkanoid and smoking outside. This shop was different from others, the building had a reputation of being haunted and people didn't really trust the meat, but salty and firm were the dumplings so prosperous and suspicious the store remained. When they called my order number i dropped my cigarette where i stood and left with the dumplings before it could hit the ground.
So warm and moist they were, the box was a small heaven for my hands as i walked through the crisp fall night. It had frozen the night before, it might again soon. Tiny daggers hit my nostrils when all i wanted was more of the savory smell from the box. Fine threadlike hints of scent hit my nostrils like honey buttered feathers against my body during a caning. I couldn't help it, I wanted a bigger whiff. I stopped beneath a flickering light and pried the lid upward. It slowly released itself with a puff of moist steam. There they were, 8 beautiful shumai tender and waiting. I couldn't bear to expose them to the elements any longer than the brief moment it took for my eyes to make my stomach jealous of my tongue's proximity to my brain which gloated heavily about the experience. I shut the lid and continued onward. A small chill went across me, i felt suddenly alone.
Several streets passed and my forearms weren't getting heat from the box anymore, my time was running out. If they cooled off they would become a repulsive mess. It's a canonical sin but i opened the box just one more time, just to check on them, maybe fill my nose again. Ahh. There they were, 7 perfect shumai with the tiniest beads of sweat on them. Soon, dumplings, soon. I closed the box and started to walk again before a sound that i've been ignoring caught up with me. My hair stood on end and my eyes searched every dark corner, for i didn't feel alone anymore.
I ordered 9 shumai and i just confirmed the status of 7 juicy and prime dumplings swollen with flavor begging to be bitten lightly into so they might burst outward. I sort of remember feeling the weight of the box when i got it and i'm sure it's the same as it is now, i've just been somewhat distracted with my surroundings. It's cold, it's dark, there are inconsistent amounts of cars and bikes parked in different areas and i really am not sure of my way around here but i'm sure the bus station is in this direction. As i wait at this intersection the wind blows my jacket around and the thin cardstock of the box began to flap. I crossed the street quickly and ducked into a nearby alcove that once served as the entrance to a disco. Flashes of memories washed over me as the neon lights tried to keep things lit.
The box was warm, I used the flickering half dead light above me to check on the remaining dumplings. Ahh, beautiful. Four ripe and slightly sticky shumai. A small slice of heaven.
I panicked. I panicked a lot longer than i'd like to admit and it wasn't a very show-y sort of panic, i just froze in place clutching the box with every fiber of my being yet without causing the box to bend or deform in any way. I clutched the air around the box so hard i cramped in both sides but i didn't notice because i was hyperventilating.
It's true, the restaurant that sells these incredible nodules of joy is located inside of a subdivided building that once was a mortuary, but the mortuary's gone so there's no problem right? Even if dead guys occupied the space of where my decadent pods of savory texture were created, that's nothing right? They wouldn't be mad at me about it? Right?!
My watch glowed in a window and i caught the time halfway through scaring myself to death and noticed i was late. If i got to the bus i'd be okay and i'd be fine and we'd eat these 4 dumplings and everyone would have a good time okay? okay. Something near me made a flapping noise.
I sprinted. I might have cried a little but i do know i screamed once when someone came outside to walk their dog and most people in this city didn't have dogs that big and i couldn't clear it. I sprinted and when i was out of breath i jogged the rest of the way to the bus stop. I dropped the box on the bench and i dropped my butt on the ground and i dropped my head at a bad angle on the side of the bench so i was slightly underneath the bench clutching my head being angry at everything in the world when the bus stopped.
I composed myself and felt sane and part of society again, the cold artificial lights and the sneers from the passengers on board assured me that my torment was over. I hope in my thrashing and wailing i didn't mess up the dumplings though. As i approached the bus i opened the box and found no shumai, not one glamorous morsel.
I shrieked for more than a little while and dropped the box, it fell upside down and my bag fell on it and i ran to the bus that had already closed it's doors and begun driving away. I tripped and lost my balance and the bus turned the corner leaving me in the dark under a dim amber lamp illuminating the haunted box. In a fit of frightened rage i kicked my bag off of the box and the box flipped over and landed open, and that is when I saw it... I saw... 9 shumai, stuck to the bottom of the lid.
